<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,152,1299]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[198,301,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is similar to the two other species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Matsumura" authorityName="Matsumura" box="[1030,1351,1041,1067]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neolimnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="egyptiacus">
<emphasis box="[1030,1049,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1065,1190,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">egyptiacus</emphasis>
(Matsumura)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Dlabola" authorityName="Dlabola" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neolimnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="superlaminatus">
<emphasis box="[1409,1428,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,333,1080,1105]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">superlaminatus</emphasis>
Dlabola
</taxonomicName>
, in external appearance and from the former species in the unusual posterior lobe of the first valvifer and apically twisted first valvulae with dorsal teeth, the latter teeth reminiscent of those found in the unrelated 
<taxonomicName box="[341,471,1157,1182]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Cicadulina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[341,471,1157,1182]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Cicadulina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Knight &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Webb" box="[654,797,1157,1183]" pageId="18" pageNumber="21" refString="Webb, M. D. &amp; Godoy, C. (1993) Review of the leafhopper tribe Scaphytopiini (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: Deltocephalinae) with a key to genera. Journal of Natural History, 27, 423 - 427." type="journal article" year="1993">
Webb, 
<number box="[736,797,1157,1183]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1993.0">1993</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 
<number box="[858,906,1157,1183]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="142.0">142</number>
). It is also similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1153,1278,1157,1182]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neolimnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="egyptiacus">
<emphasis box="[1153,1278,1157,1182]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">egyptiacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is the only other species known from the male, in the short subgenital plate with an unusual inner dorsal process (
<figureCitation box="[159,233,1234,1260]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,205,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1436,194,1583]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 6. Neolimnus quadricornis sp. nov., male genitalia, a, b, genital capsule, lateral and dorsal view respectively; c, anal tube, dorsal view; d, valve subgenital plate, style and connective, dorsal view; e – g aedeagus, posterior view, ventral view and lateral view respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/193664/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Figs 
<number box="[218,233,1234,1260]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
d, 
<quantity box="[261,294,1234,1260]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="7.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="g" value="7.0">7g</quantity>
). It differs from this species by its more elongate pygofer and very different aedeagus with a more elongate and evenly tapered shaft (compare figs 
<quantity box="[719,749,1273,1299]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="6.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="g" value="6.0">6g</quantity>
and 
<number box="[806,821,1273,1299]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="7.0">7</number>
e) with two pair of lateral process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
